|}

==First millennium AD==
From [[Late Antiquity]], we have for the first time languages with earliest records in [[manuscript]] tradition (as opposed to [[epigraphy]]). Thus, [[Old Armenian]] is first attested in the [[Armenian Bible translation]].

The [[Vimose inscriptions]] (2nd and 3rd centuries) in the [[Elder Futhark]] runic alphabet appear to record [[Proto-Norse language|Proto-Norse]] names. Some scholars interpret the [[Negau helmet]] inscription ({{circa|lk=no}} 100 BC) as a Germanic fragment.
